According to [this article](https://www.pcg-random.org/posts/bounded-rands.html), the "FP Multiply" method used by lodash's `random()` function is not 100% unbiased -- some integers will show up (very slightly) more than others.

Line in question: https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/2f79053d7bc7c9c9561a30dda202b3dcd2b72b90/random.js#L70

Equivalent code in the article: (under "FP Multiply (Biased)")
```
static uint32_t bounded_rand(rng_t& rng, uint32_t range) {
    double zeroone = 0x1.0p-32 * rng();
    return range * zeroone;
}
```

> This approach is just as biased as the classic modulo approach, but the bias manifests itself differently. For example, if we were choosing numbers in the range [0..52), the numbers 0, 13, 26 and 39 would appear once less often than the others.

Basically, the number of floating point values representable is (usually) not a multiple of the number of integer results in the target range, meaning some integers have one fewer floating-point value that maps to them -- creating a small bias.

The article provides various approaches that can be used to remove that small bias.

`_.merge` will not recursively merge **nested** objects instantiated from the **same constructor**. Expected behavior is like a recursive Object.assign()

```
class RoomData {
  constructor(room) {
     this._room = room;
  }
}

let base = {_roomData: new RoomData('room')}
let delta = {_roomData: new RoomData()}
let merged = _.merge(base, delta);
console.log(merged)
// expected: Object {_roomData: RoomData {_room: 'room'}}
// got: Object {_roomData: RoomData {_room: undefined}}

// Proof that RoomData objects are not being recursively merged, but rather the _roomData reference is just reassigned
console.log(merged._roomData === delta._roomData)
// expected: false
// got: true

// What if we use object literals?
_.merge({_roomData:{_room: 'a'}}, {_roomData:{}})
// works as expected: Object {_roomData: Object {_room: "a"}}

// What if the objects aren't nested?
_.merge(new RoomData('room'), new RoomData());
// works as expected: Object {_room: "room"}
```

I think a `keyValueBy` function would be a welcome addition to the package.
The idea is to minimize reduce structures like the following example:

```
const dictionary = options.reduce((map: Record<string, object>, option) => {
    map[`label_${option.label}`] = option.value || defaultValue;
    return map;
}, {});
```

This functionality is partially covered by the existing `keyBy` function, meaning `keyBy` function lets you create a dictionary with mapping logic for the keys of the resulting dictionary (e.g.: ``` option => `label_${option.label}` ``` ), but the `keyBy` function doesn't allow mapping logic for the values of the resulting dictionary, like the fallback logic in the example above. That functionality is covered in the `mapValue`, so a combination of both does the trick I guess:
```
const dictionary = mapValues(keyBy(options, option => `label_${option.label}`), option => option.value || defaultValue);
```

But it would be nice to have this in a single function, like so:
```
const dictionary = keyValueBy(options, option => `label_${option.label}`, option => option.value || defaultValue);
```

And of course in simpler cases which don't require lambda logic, this function would be very welcome as well:
```
const dictionary = keyValueBy(options, 'label', 'value');
```

